Higgs' boson shelled
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole stir last summer, and for cause.
We believe that this boson is involved in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is the Higgs.
We know without a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data released this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely sure.
Let us assume, however, that it is the Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem slim, and let us see what this is about.
There is, in this world, a inevitably inevitable law that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're gonna hurt yourself.
But even if the physics of particles is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In a corner there are good citizens named fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And in the other one the bosons, a dirty gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything - in any case, not for this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, moreover) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not approach here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature spread and to which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosoms, it must be pointed out here, are not all as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" which is the "messager" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field in this precise place, a bit like a rock thrown into a pond.
From this "derangement" arises an electromagnetic wave (of light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore, one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More stable field
It is the same with the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
However, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to reach very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond whose only very large rock could ride the surface.
This is why it takes a huge particle accelerator like that of CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring of 27 km of circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between Higgs and mass.
It is not all particles, nor all materials, that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do it, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on a fridge.
And in the same way, it is not all particles that interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while others (like the photon, here) do not.
Now, what can "bring" all this research, asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to examine any discrepancies between MS observations and predictions.
In fact, there are a number of people who are eager to find them, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and close some of the holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has huge deficiencies, offering no explanation for gravity (ops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-ops!).
But we haven't found any such deviations at CERN so far.
Impacts
The impact of this research on the daily lives of Mr. and Mrs. All-the-World is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
At the very beginning of the 1960s, laser pioneers in the Bell Laboratories had no suspicion of the revolution that their work was about to start.
They could see scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, we have already told us the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 - the laser was initially seen as a "lab gadget".
Imagine...
And then, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his optical work.
This sensor, although not at all its original intention, now serves as an "eye" to all digital cameras in the world, and has earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This does not mean, of course, that LHC activities will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that, really, you never know...
Palliative care - The best way to die...
With its Commission dying in dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is expected to resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this crucial area.
The Devoir tried to take a closer look at it.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that gnawed him had left him with a two-year respite.
"They had given me five years to live, I had seven years," he said, half-raisin fig, lying in his bed at Victor Gadbois Palliative Care House in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease is doing its job: a huge weakness that prevents it from going to the toilet alone, and even from eating alone.
Attacked in front of an appetizing lunch, he agreed to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, speaks to strangers who work around him, bring him his medicine, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is for me to be cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man is pissing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois.
Regressing to the child's stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability to accept regression," he says.
For, in the opinion of many people working in palliative care, great moments are taking place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients entering the Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care Home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life prognosis of three months.
At this point, the "team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so - called "curative care. "
For 89-year-old Mrs. A., the worst fear is to die "conscious and suffocated".
But the disease made me discover my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life," she said, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting, in the next few days, for a last visit by her son from Italy.
With a group of volunteers, Victor Gadbois provides body care and food aid.
It's palliative care, which you give when there's nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when you know that you all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions," explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the home's doctors.
Whether in physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
If you die, you will be willing to give mouth care to the brandy or Pepsi, as required.
Diabetes patients will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died during the night.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
" We help loved ones as much as patients, " says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow but don't look alike.
Along with an old 93 - year - old man who savors his last family meeting in the courtyard, well settled in his pillows while he is being trined in his honour, a 36 - year - old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children, after trying everything to survive.
" For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45, " says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home arrive from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problems of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e., care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal phase of his or her life, whether at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And many organizations, such as the Victor Gadbois House and the Society for Palliative Home Care in Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec health care that makes several palliative care physicians fear the adoption of legislation to regulate euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, of the leaders of palliative care, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health care system is not effective enough to ensure that everyone is entitled to quality palliative care before they agree to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency, in great pain, without doing anything to relieve her.
I'm afraid patients only ask to die because they don't get the proper care.
And at the same time, several oncologists hound on their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hélène Richard's survival expectations were already minimal when she gave up trying chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
But she told me I was done!
Not all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not accepting their request after they have been relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, Director of Palliative Care at the Society of Palliative Home Care in Greater Montreal, patients would be resistant to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which amounts to sleeping the patient until his death, either sporadically or permanently.
You can't pretend you don't hear that part of the suffering anymore.
More and more, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same sentence: "I want to die. "
But it doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to euthanize me," it means "I want to be relieved."
