A Constitution with forceps in Egypt
It's a new poker shot by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, it has decided to play its all-out.
Taking everyone short, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State gave this House an additional two months to finish its work.
Egypt has been relying on a provisional text for almost two years, several times amended, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "trap his word" and "push the law".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time which obliges the Brothers to give up their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy while the challenge is raging throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote favourably, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this resort to a hasty vote is based on the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Or you vote for my text, either I keep the full powers", those supposedly to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It was in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most Liberals missed the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, considering that they could not make their views known.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, alternate members, were added hastily yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it was most often unanimously that the articles were voted on.
Commentators also had fun because one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the hour of prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the pendulum of the Constituent was not well settled.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
The object of all attention, article 2 remains finally identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to be able to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," the liberals replied, who saw it as a mere communication.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the conformity of laws with sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the first fruits of a theocracy."
The fears of the Liberals are also stirred up by the fact that the next president of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"For the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain in the framework of the Civil Status.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system" Tempère Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits that "there may be an ambiguity around article 220, because the terms used use religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, edlr].
And the question may arise in the future to what extent civilian judges are competent to rule on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced in comparison to what they were under the former regime.
Another contentious point is the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, consideration of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as requested by human rights associations.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticide.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, including the press.
In addition, there are no more articles echoing the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her view, the only positive point was the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was supposed to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned this afternoon.
The head of state's supporters will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the grandeur of Bible truths, modern comfort and wild nature.
Argumenty i Fakty has chosen five main reasons to visit Israel.
Go and worship the holy places
Make yourself inevitable: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone entering these "baptismal lands" will be touched by divine Grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of Jesus' miracles: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on water, where he calmed the storm, or where the fishing was miraculous.
It was in this precise place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
The believers travel through the Rue de la Sufferance or the Way of the Cross (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the pretoire), where the trial was held, then led by the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Anointing and the burial.
Here lies the Christian center of the world, symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem also houses the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wall of Lamentations, which constitutes the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 B.C.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave small words with prayers, which are then answered.
Travel high
Visit the ruins of the fortress Massada, former refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain at 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can get there by their own means.
For others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, there is the Mont Hermont ski resort, which welcomes many tourists in the winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are 45 km long in total.
Old beliefs want pagan gods to have once lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth the detour.
First of all: the Museum of Israel located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It houses the ancient manuscripts of Qumran, or manuscripts of the Dead Sea, discovered in the caves of the Judea Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
Also to be seen: the Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
The paintings of Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso are exhibited.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of casts of visitors and overseers of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin's sculptures.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the children's memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars are sparkling.
You then hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and welfare
Israel's three major seaside resorts are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, delphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, because the water temperature does not fall below 21° while the air temperature can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can bathe there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point of the Earth, 417 m below sea level.
Azur-coloured water contains brine and very easily retains bathers, even those who can't swim.
The landscapes surrounding it are surreal beauty.
We come here to perform a treatment based on salt water, silt, curative sludge and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by the old town of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially like to walk in narrow alleys that bear the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you will be able to meet newlyweds who come to take photos of all Israel and even other countries.
At Caesarea, King Herod's city, you can walk around the Roman theatre, "capture " the Crusader's Fortress.
During the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera shows.
Note to tourists
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer the dollars to the euro, because they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
In terms of urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and capable of connecting the lower and upper parts of the city.
It's almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition is to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturdays.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturdays, markets, shops and public transport cease their activity.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes consisting of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts based on coconut milk, but also hummus, traditional Jewish paste, different sauces, ground chickpea balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-nourished cats that walk the haughty air.
We can see them sleeping at night on the roofs of parked cars.
These felines love places passing by and don't refuse to enjoy them.
The rental of a car varies according to the brand from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
An entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The language of the numbers
Three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mainly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists travelled to the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before visa cancellation on February 9, 2011.
"Who language has, in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
As MPs and human rights activists argue about what the law on compulsory language testing will give, fraudsters selling "false" certificates have already appeared in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are nationals of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families stay at home.
Since 1 December, a law had entered into force and stipulated that every migrant worker would have to pass a Russian examination.
For the time being, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, testing will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the history of Russia and the foundations of law.
You will need to validate your language knowledge in Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt.
Persons who obtained education certificates or diplomas prior to the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not covered by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be under the auspices of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, the University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take examinations in all the cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what will it give?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, the representatives of the migration service reply, this will help to reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery to work".
Many speak of defending the rights of migrant workers, explains Victor Sebelev, director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan.
Protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without the understanding of the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, on the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellows will be tormented for months without food and paper and will have to trim between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive numerous complaints from our migrants.
"In them, one thing is promised, and when they arrive, they are deceived, their passports are taken, and they do not receive the expected salary," confirms the Head of the Directorate of Migration Services for Work of the Migration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Charipov.
Don't argue with me, policeman!
However, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to come and earn money in Russia entrust that they do not only know the language of the country they wish to visit, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
Of course it is not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to attend even a fair primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children, not to mention to dress them properly and equip them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to earn money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It's difficult when you don't know the language, they confide.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the language law.
The examinations will be intended only for migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no formal examination or work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or defend from entering"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain an official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and still these linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 miles rubles.
And then, you can get a fake record quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we have no registration, hence the cases of extortion.
"They ask us 100, 200 rubles, enough to buy cigarettes, tea," said journalists Oumed Khushkadamov, a national of Tajikistan.
"Make it quick, don't squeak and buy yourself a beautiful piece of art"
From the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that migrants' registration papers were not the only ones to be false.
Several false certificates of language examinations have already been confiscated by the employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Falsified papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not have them for nothing: every migrant who hoped thus to facilitate the task of the examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The representatives of power and human rights defenders agree that the short-term objective is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "paper bits".
The authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the examination at first time the time to take language courses.
Moreover, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The proportion of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against civilian arms carriers.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it was the shooting at the weddings or the killing organized by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven people.
The police want to prohibit the wearing of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a licence to carry a weapon from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee for Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that the amendments to the Arms Act would be introduced in the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "squeezing the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centres, demanded to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, told the Russian service Vasily Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services, while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded in the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that the strengthening of civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from purchasing from the black market.
According to them, today we can find in Moscow any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior claims that it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black arms market is supplied via several channels.
There are five main channels, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served 10 years at the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking command of weapons
The first is "the military trace", i.e. the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians," says Baranets.
The second type of black market weapons are those stolen from law enforcement by criminals.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stocks and weapons stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
The illegal pistols go for sale from the military warehouses.
Many of these have often experienced explosions.
"Certified versions indicate that some fires have been deliberately triggered to cover up the deficit," explains the former member.
For Baranets, the gun manufacturers are doing something about it.
"There are private arms factories that do not compete with competition on the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow," says one expert.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
A large proportion of pistols and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply," the former soldier adds.
Where did the guns come from?
Experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on this issue was established in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Specialists analysed the reports of the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, the criminal files and the public data of the arms portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the army and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found there "by fault of the employees whose work is related to weapons", the report explains.
According to researchers, 17% of weapons come from military conflict sites, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from "smuggling".
A seller and consultant of an armory who asked to remain anonymous ensures that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these underground search specialists; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, sellers will pick up new goods in military warehouses.
The person buys a unit through a sign, e.g. a TT gun.
We deliver it to him by means of a grill.
"He transports it to the city and sells it for 900 € by the unit with two chargers," he says.
