A joint inspection by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
He cites Petr Nečas' approach to the " Švarc system" as an example of abusive practice.
The Prime Minister recently stated that the SDO would not interfere with contractors with controls, so is it permitted or prohibited?
"The law must be applied in one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority from going to inspect to demand compliance with the law," Kala says.
At the meeting of the Monitoring Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you referred to a Czech-German project in which the legislation on public procurement in these two countries was compared.
What was it really about?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and specific national legislation, as well as a practice itself.
We have gathered all this together and although this monitoring procedure has not yet been completed, very interesting differences have emerged: generally speaking, our legislation may be "more severe and of better quality", but according to certain parameters, practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms, therefore, that it is not enough to continually elaborate more and more detailed rules, but that it is necessary to devote itself to the implementation of the law itself.
How can this project help you in practice and what is the result for you?
A common control of this kind should help us to stop trying to clarify laws, lower and improve thresholds, where this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means getting the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But lowering market thresholds will not necessarily achieve this goal.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by paperwork, that those looking for faults will find much more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal problems concerning the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an institution similar to our SAI or a different way of organizing it?
As far as the institutions, like the ISC, are concerned, the Bundesrechnungshof, which is organised in a similar way, also has a council formed a little differently, but these two institutions basically proceed in a similar way.
The competences are also, to a certain extent, similar, but with a certain degree of difference in relation to our system: Germany is a federal structure, so it also has such accounts at the level of the various Länder.
The ORH can only control federal money, which in our case corresponds to the resources of the state.
The public funds administered at home by the regions and municipalities are controlled there at the level of the Länder' accounts.
As far as national legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas Germany is often referred to as a model, but it certainly cannot be said that it does better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better detectives?
No, I'm sure not, but I repeat, I don't have any comparative data.
However, it must also be said that this country, which we consider to be a model, is also facing a whole series of problems.
Otherwise they wouldn't have any advantage in cooperating with our institution, would they?
As far as national legislation is concerned, what has the amendment of the law on public procurement meant for you as an institution, and what effect has it already had?
As this amendment has entered into force relatively recently, it does not yet have an impact on our control operations.
As we do ex post checks, we have to count with a certain delay.
