The problem that may arise is that these rules become more stringent and cannot be respected.
Already under the previous regulation, the provider (e.g. the Regional Council, in the case of regional operational programmes) forced controlled subjects to accept that any breach of the contract law meant a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it really useful to make the law more severe in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or abuse the system but not punish those who make formal mistakes without consequences for the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what's the solution for getting out of it?
Let's look where we're not going.
