Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as a twentieth member of the Agency, it is the second Member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and in subsequent years participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, Poland's road to space began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to refer, for example, to the A. Šternfeld conference at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, at which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld obtained the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch awards in France for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books on this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a promoter of world-renowned astronautics, his contribution has been rewarded in particular by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the Moon.
As early as 1925, in Poland, a draisine was built to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also not clear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the rites.
The only known information on this trait is from the press of the time.
From 1933 Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the documents kept that this research had reached the test stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, the drawings of a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author called Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were aimed at the military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all rocket technology projects were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, further work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish astronautic company Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne.
For the first time, a company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of Problem, in which there are four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautism.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish astronautic company (PTA) made efforts to join the international astronautic federation (established in 1951) and in the autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the PTA's first president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice-President of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the weather rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologicczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
This rocket, with a range of 1800 metres, was 80 cm long and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently an improved version was built, RM-1A and, in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-storey RM-2 rocket were started in the Bledov Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 metres long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962-1965, succeeded the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space volume of 0.4 litres, while in Meteor-1B the volume was 0.34 litres and in Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all these types of equipment was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aviation institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a COSPAR national committee two years later are worth mentioning.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in the space exploration on the Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of the programme.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision raised a strong debate in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to examine this issue from a broader perspective.
Liberalist economic systems, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means in concrete terms that the different economic entities and national economic systems are constantly in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of free trade and free (without limits) movement of private capital, combined with unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in labour prices (wages) create a price tension.
Under this term, a producer is trying to import low-priced goods to resist economic competition by "making the competitor's price more expensive", with the aim of removing a greater share of the market and thereby increasing its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad, buying cheaply, or disappearing. The result is a high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the state's social charges necessarily increase.
This situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of businessmen to pay taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
Unscrupulous practices of private capital create a situation in the various economies in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population with the aim of attracting foreign capital to them.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking into account the social collapse.
This is reflected mainly in the amendments to the laws in force.
The aim is to force its own population to accept the diktat of private capital prices, particularly in the area of wages.
This occurs, on the one hand, by a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and, on the other hand, by restricting the rights of employees in the field of labour legislation.
This results in increasing poverty and deepening the differences between the rich and the poor.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, for years there have been public food distribution points for the poor who cannot support themselves with their own work.
There are already millions of such people.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the State is forced to pay a supplement so that they reach the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal has, for example, been updated in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of virtually all the southern EU Member States are undoubtedly generating a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century) or to subjugate with wages of misery, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day private capital will invest in their country.
Here we have to ask ourselves the question: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will go from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European wage.
This also concerns Latin America as a whole.
Liberal theory and the media say, getting tired of it, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the directed economy leads to an economic disaster.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the State cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
We must then ask ourselves whether private capital does not influence and, even today, does not, according to its own selfish interests, lead politics and by the same, the entire state.
The answer to this question is certainly yes.
The evidence is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby present in all States.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is reprehensible but not punishable.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that, due to the lack of financial resources, the national ministries delegate the preparation of draft laws to law firms closely linked to industry.
These bills are then adopted in the Bundestag.
The entire power does not come from the people, as Western-style constitutions say, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberalist democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Time of Caesar and Pompey": "The State had long been in a state of collapse and functions were attributed by violence.
The bribes, the favors obtained illegally, and the stones and swords were also used to obtain these posts.
It was true that Appianos had in mind Pompey, but it was Caesar who irreversibly transformed democracy into an absoluteist regime.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, regardless of the interest of society as a whole.
In essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and assert the interests of society as a whole.
The result, today as in the past, is a decadence without precedents for elites, without any effort to carry out far-reaching reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
As things stand, we can see the disappearance of these systems in favour of liberal democracies as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises we are witnessing today, and the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and internally in Europe, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution consists of socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investments in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
