The Argo movie: when everything goes to the worst, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protestors made up of Islamist students stormed the American embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had been supporting his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the American administration a positive outcome, it could not abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously undermined the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of the hostages.
It was a hard blow for the prestige of the United States, further aggravated by the fiasco of the attempt to free hostages by force.
The detained diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate gave rise to a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle contributed strongly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered America a small victory.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated adventures, they found themselves in the Canadian ambassador's residence.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran thanks to a rock cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who came to make spottings for a big science fiction film.
Combination of genera
The exfiltration expert Tony Mendez's plan required Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
On the one hand, it is a political thriller conceived realistically but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful coup, of a treachery - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean's even, twelve and thirteen.
The atmospheres follow one another: sequences of Tehran in documentary style (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and the way in which, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed in the film, there are no great differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
And then scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to reboot his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting game ceased to arouse ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark policeman " Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also the first Affleck film that does not take place in its original city, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo, where the role of Tehran "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity, which also suggests confusion and unpredictability when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect in the fictitious scenes (the fake filming team in Tehran's bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to content himself with a subject offering in fact few exciting scenes, in the cinematic sense of the term.
He is doing very well, he sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is ruled out by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the airstrip is quite drawn by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in its dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have deserved a greater place and they are not, far from it, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks some dramatic tension, it lets itself be seen with moderate interest, appreciating the realization and retro style of the 1970s.
He trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story still, in a certain way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the trick.
