The architects of the firm MVRDV prove that the real adventures are not only a matter of imagination. To convince yourself, you just have to contemplate Spijkenisse and the mountain of newly erected books - 2 photos
"I think this building is fun, it is very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist in a large nearby company, tells us: "Yes, it is indeed beautiful, this building".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one goes to one of these ringuard libraries of his own free will, no?
Spijkenisse, a dormant city that has nothing to do with Rotterdam, has a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brains, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro notes in the form of pretty small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
Thus the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control of statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, of the architect's office in Rotterdam MVRDV, master of diagrams in bold sticks and creator of buildings full of mind and often cynical, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and presented himself to the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a laugh on his face.
And while the jury members were still looking at each other, disconcerted and uplifting their shoulders, Maas, the frightful, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make it a pyramid, and finished his speech supported by militant arguments with one: "common auction!"
Here it is, my proposal for the book mountain of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain has come out of the earth.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and houses for a total of 50 homes.
At the beginning of November, the book mountain was awarded the second Best Library of NL 2012 prize.
In addition, the project was selected for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
Thus, this dull little village, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall with an amazing ugliness, whose white facades suggest that they are home to a dairy, has enriched itself with a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to reading
First impression: Eldorado of the cheese bell book.
Of course, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open to you when you tread the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant street lights speak unequivocally the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking at public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and books.
"Normally, library shelves are located along the facade and in the middle is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," says Willy Maas.
We have completely changed the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the book mountain has been adeptly arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the centre for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes panelling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stair ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and engineers don't want any unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
One day we found in a Frisian farm an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, the synthetic membrane of one millimetre thick has been used for many years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're saving time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates of a thickness of four centimetres.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic " (KPL) changes colour and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary café offers a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and pot ficuses.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal level of humidity in the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's amazing, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model ecological project," says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is controlled by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun only brightens the interior for a short time, even on days of good weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted across from the glass facade serve as sun visors, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The ambient atmosphere is very pleasant.
The completely automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned septician, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "soul finally recovered".
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This has made it possible to fill the voids of the library which was not yet fully stocked (today it has 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I think our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has reached the master discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse wrote a new page of literary history.
Even though she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose abstention in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a difficult political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but was not too critical of Israel.
During the insurgency in Libya in March 2011, Germany also chose to abstain in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Is it difficult for Germany to adopt a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so much defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans thus face several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that they are still trying to find this role, but are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including on national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, hence by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position with regard to the conflict in the Middle East and its abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to hit public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive factor in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany damage its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think that the fracture is not so serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus shown that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions about the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, publicly defend its position.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you observe the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from exceedingly enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think it makes things easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today that is not the case.
They cannot therefore form part of a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
That is what they are doing now in the question of the euro.
In my view, Germany will assume a locomotive role in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not simple for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive issue.
But in my view, the Germans are well aware of the fact that they must play a role that further marks their independence.
Does Germany have a role to play as a major player on the international stage, and does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does she still have difficulty taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still has difficulties in playing a more important role.
Looking at, for example, the euro crisis, we note that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German sentiments are heard.
It doesn't make things easy for the Germans.
In fact, it is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
She has to deal with a wide variety of neighbours and opinions, and it's not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only diminishing, but at the moment, the EU is not filling this void, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and they're less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyze the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
