In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell almost only counterfeits.
Pattloch's cases are, however, different: its applicants direct him to address the fact that the Chinese trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese are talking about "Bang Mingpai", a relative brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is with this term that women who marry rich men are referred to.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame.
"It's bad for business, we have to fight this trend," Pattloch demands.
"The brand is sweetened, singularity disappears, the damage to reputation is enormous."
Financial losses and legal costs amount to millions for the sectors concerned, especially for expensive flagship products.
According to data from the CLSA market analysis company, China represents, with an annual volume of 15 billion euros, the world's third largest luxury market and the fastest growing market.
However, it is not easy to remove doubtful registrations from the trademark register and these procedures are expensive.
The latter can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch refers to the trials in which the court rejected the complaint, because after a long period of time, the name criticized had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains to us that if the complainant is not lucky, he may even be forced to pay the plagiarist money because he would have harmed his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against the construction company Sany, the same company that had just purchased the concrete pump producer Putzmeister.
That's why the Chinese can use an emblem that looks like the Mercedes star.
