The fashion house Lacoste had lost against the plagiars of Hong Kong and Singapore who had reoriented the gaze of the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing admits, however, that it experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, last year the Office would have moved from an "emergency situation in the course of work to a normality regained".
Thus, the number of unprocessed opposition proceedings would have decreased by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases would have been closed, an increase of 75% over the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 proceedings remain pending at the Office.
Taking action is expensive
As is often the case in China, the figures are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received over 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the Office, this is a record, and this means that China is the tenth consecutive leader in the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal trademarks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the Office reportedly accounted for 1.8 billion yuan of registration fees.
In other words, each record earned an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as the case of the German family company Freudenberg illustrates.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting against a Chinese plagiarist.
Of course, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights over the Freudenberg brand.
"It's our fault, because last names cannot be protected in Germany," says Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The Trademark Office had therefore rejected the Munichers' objection.
Freudenberg certainly won in the next two instances, but the opposing side continues to fight until today.
Vigilance is necessary
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, believes in a positive outcome of the trial and boasts the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds: "the procedure is long, difficult and costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to estimate internal costs. The archives department has even had to review the acts of the last hundred years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg even proposed in vain to the opposing party a "large sum in euros with six digits" to settle the dispute.
"That's what we see for ourselves," Wentzler says.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to overflow into Europe.
This would be the case if imitators in this region ensured the exploitation of unprotected trademarks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to file in Germany the name of Freudenberg for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long abandoned this sector, but it was still able to prevent the deposit.
Wentzler adds: "the vigilance is in order".
Pattloch and he advise German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, in their view, to rely on international trademark law; rather, foreigners should "register also in China everything that is likely to be protected", as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs may be much higher than the costs of registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of its legal drama, the company would have to pay license fees to the opposing party for the use of its own name, as Wentzler explains.
Or we would lose our place in the segment of the market in question.
