Bradley Manning did not complain about ill-treatment, the prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter claims of ill-treatment allegedly suffered by Bradley Manning during detention.
The trial involved the detention of Manning in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence wants to close the case on the grounds that Manning's kidnapping took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to demonstrate on Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of causing the biggest leak of confidential information in the history of the U.S. Army -- has missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein claimed that recordings of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not reveal any complaints regarding his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a motion requiring the Manning case to be closed on the grounds that the kidnapping was carried out under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning testified to his desire to commit suicide while in detention.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning had been their source.
At the Friday hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers had completed after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in Quantico Military Prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that his guards' treatment was "excellent" and that his treatment in the prison was generally "very professional."
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had orally expressed concerns about certain issues and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the problems raised.
"They wrote "no problem" (after addressing concerns), but that didn't mean I didn't raise any problems," Manning said.
Military judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to change his restrictive status indicating a "risk of injury".
The members stated that they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for risk of suicide -- for his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know I was okay, and I wanted to be removed from my status... in order to enjoy a better quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at Marine Corps Base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He stated that he had considered suicide while in Kuwait and had fainted once because of the heat.
He added that the fact that he was not aware of what was going to happen to him or what was going on in the rest of the world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning stated that he had spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had at his disposal were mattresses, blankets, flip-flops, clothes and glasses.
He tried to stay in motion, because sleeping or lying during the day was contrary to the rules.
Manning also said that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned around at night, they woke him up so that they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint regarding Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Levenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony on Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked one night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other detainees one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the appeal.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning stated that he had deduced from his guard's order that he should release his cover that could have hidden his nudity, but he admitted that no one had ordered him to let go.
Manning testified on Thursday that he was forced to sleep naked the night before, as he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning allegedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his briefs or flip-flops to hurt himself, but he didn't.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account his experiences during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he is convicted before a court martial, a trial that is expected to take place early next year.
The defence stated that Manning intends to plead guilty to the least serious offences and to fight for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing should resume this weekend, with prosecutors who should argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon confirmed that Manning was incarcerated in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of national defence information.
If all counts are held, he is liable to life imprisonment.
