Laws for Neutral Packages of Cigarettes have come into force in Australia
Warnings and pictures of sick organs cover the dark green packages that are all identical, whatever the brand.
This law entered into force in Australia is a world first, the logos and colors have been replaced by a dark olive green and horrific pictures of sick organs and representations of children and babies whose diseases have been caused by their parents' smoking.
Apart from the different photos and health warnings, the only difference between packages since Saturday is the name of the brand, printed in small print on all packages.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The Australian federal government stated that the goal was to discourage young people from smoking by removing glamorous portrayals.
Studies have shown that if people did not start smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that they will never start.
"Even when they are very young, children understand the message conveyed by tobacco manufacturers through their brand image," said Federal Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have revealed, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with a princess."
