The problem is that it has been defined and debated in different ways, said John D. Eastwood, Associate Professor of Psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After going through many publications and submitting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience that consists of "wanting to do something, but without succeeding in engaging in a satisfactory activity."
What differentiates boredom from apathy, he says, is that the person is not undertaking a task although they would like to.
With apathy, he says, there is no desire to do something.
