The hardest job in the world: Kawah Ijen's human mules
For four euros, Indonesian volcano carriers risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through steep stone trails.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living wearing the sulfur of the Kawah Ijen volcano in eastern Indonesia's Java island.
He must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphuric gas from the earth's bowels solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large sulfur rocks, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep trails.
There are only 250 meters to the top of the volcano that peaks at 2,386 meters above sea level, but the worn-out porters take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a tortoise-like look, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a fatal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents of euro for every kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once at the top, he makes a way between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and painfully carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the balance that a mining company installed a little below at 1,850 meters altitude.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, as we can say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it at 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in daily life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even used to bleach sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes 3 hours and ends exhausted, but it allows him to win 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although this seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is the triple of what he would gain in the fields.
"The income of the miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly wage is 2 million rupees (167 euros), " says the porter who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, her salary was Rs 75,000 (6.20 euros) a day and the job wasn't as difficult, but Anto returned to her family in Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that in Indonesia is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, he spent three of his life defying the danger on the Kawah ljen, but sulphur has already begun to make him pay the bill although he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases rejected by the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work for another two years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in an English more than acceptable.
Maltreated by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
It shares an unsanitary wooden masure with other bearers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because sulphur does not cease to spring at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater by lighting himself with a small lamp fixed to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to the wearers who work on their own and are paid by weight.
In addition, they do not receive a sub of the 30,000 rupees (EUR 2.50) of mark-up per camera, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (EUR 1.20), which the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is done for animals, not humans," protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old corpulent carrier who has been working in Kawah Ijen for thirty years, since he left college.
Capable of carrying up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, between the ages of 10 and 18.
I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulphur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick smoke columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... to which are obviously added their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pains in the knees and shoulders, distorted by the weight of the baskets.
By balancing the basket on his back, 53-year-old Unainik can only load 50 kilos.
Every day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano, which three trucks carry to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometres away by a path of goats invaded by weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life," says Unainik, opening his mouth well, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of his five children, aged 30, also works as a bearer of sulphur.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation, one of the most difficult occupations in the world: the human mules of the Kawah ljen volcano.
Singapore seeks babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame this lack of children for the career, stress and cost of accessing property.
"Singapore's people must grow."
I am a husband and a patriot, you are my wife and a patriot, fulfill our civic duty and give life!
It may seem unlikely that these words come from an advertisement for mint pellets, but despite that, or perhaps because of that, the video spread like a drag of powder on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lyrics come from a rap group that uses local references like "Let's put a policinelle in the drawer" to make fun of Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency at the origin of the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a fun way thanks to this advertising.
His creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music to ensure that people fulfilled "their national duty."
It is intended solely for the Internet, so we were able to make it entertaining and fun.
This is the main problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the field of birth, so we felt that it was a theme we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried several things, such as throwing perfumes at pheromones or organizing speed-dating parties.
Many of these ideas were creative, but they didn't necessarily work.
So we said the following: What's more creative about solving this problem than making it a rap song?
1.2 children
The government of Singapore does not take it so lightly.
It spends US$1,300 a year in politics to encourage its citizens to have more children.
A government measure for marriages and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a rich and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
Singapore ' s birth rate, according to its national population distribution, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered to be the rate of renewal, was in 1976.
Why, then, do Singaporeans not have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policies of the National Population Division, says it is due to "better education" and "a wider choice of career opportunities".
"This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and family formation," she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the increase in the number of single women and to the delaying of marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
In the meantime, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that abound in xenophobia barely disguised against new immigrants, especially against Chinese who are accused of pulling wages down and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the party in Singapore last year experienced its worst election results since independence.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem with the introduction of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While falling birth rates have known effects on a country's economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore's example also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, this has begun to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to monitor the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", which can be built in specific areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, the authorities are concerned that they can promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, managing director of the EL Developers real estate company, claims that its "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these houses are being built much faster than larger ones.
For this reason, it's much more profitable for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new standards provide clearer instructions to promoters, who were previously put in the wheels if they wanted to offer too many small housing units in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If these new regulations can be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by discussing with Singaporeans working in the financial district of the centre, it would seem that they will not have much effect.
"People are very stressed, homes are expensive, just like education, that's why people put it to a later stage," says a young executive.
Other people can have children.
"But for me, it's important to be able to dispose of my money and my time," says another 20-year-old.
Men and women refer to their careers, stress and the cost of access to property and education as the reasons preventing them from having children.
Thus, while the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans themselves have the last word.
