And if Sweden, as fully permitted by its legislation, and as it has already done in other cases, questioned Mr Assange in the Embassy of Ecuador in London, or questioned him via Skype tomorrow, the problem would also be solved.
Correa took the opportunity to reaffirm himself as a defender of press freedom and said that what he did not tolerate was "the mediocrity, bad faith and lies that harm freedom of expression".
"The biggest enemies of press freedom are not malevolent or perverse politicians, but the bad journalists who pay for greed, blackmail and extortion," he said.
From this perspective, he welcomed that it was not this type of journalists "not the bankers or the hegemonic and bourgeois countries that dominate in Ecuador" and, rather than putting forward his re-election, "he would deepen the revolution in order to continue the path and chart the right path".
Correa also supported the decision to keep the veto on Paraguay within the Unasur at least until the next elections, arguing that the organization "should be firm and not tolerate opportunism and disguised coup attempts", because in reality "it was destroying the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
Moreover, the President of Ecuador considers as "perfectly relevant" the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries through the judgment of the International Court of The Hague, which will strengthen Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty.
For the time being, this judgment is not respected.
This is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to move forward together.
We have to solve them as a whole in order to overcome them and move forward.
At the same time, he expressed confidence in the proper resolution of the maritime border dispute between Peru and Chile in the same court and affirmed that it is "beneficial for Latin America to seize international forums if both countries agree to accept a judgment as firm as it is".
Referring to the possibility of his nomination as a candidate in the upcoming presidential elections in Ecuador, in order to run for a third consecutive term, he pointed out that he saw this possibility "with great optimism and joy, although it is sometimes quite difficult".
Correa assured that if he lost the February 2013 primary, he would withdraw from public life.
At the personal level, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unfair as those of Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be resolved through political power.
"My political movement believed that it was I who guaranteed this eventual victory, but we must accept this responsibility," he said.
If I win, it would be my last presidential term and then I will withdraw from political life.
If we ever lose, I'll do it too.
"This is my decision," he said.
Correa also referred to the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just talked to Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that routine medical treatment was already planned and that he was waiting for the end of the campaign to return to Cuba.
"This does not mean a relapse in President Chávez's state of health," he commented.
