AIDS-related deaths are now due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed to be HIV positive.
"It was as if the sky had fallen on my head," he said, referring to the time of the announcement, that the doctor had tried to make "less painful", in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to inquire about him and his hard work was such that he had just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV Unit at the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, where there were many doubts, few treatment choices and more stigmas.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because he was speechless."
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and to have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "exhausted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the onset of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same", said the head of the HIV unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva and he takes as a reference that this information was validated in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
The HIV/AIDS infectious and expert, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a life-threatening disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depend on the level of assignment of the immune system that patients have at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years for a CD4 rate of 200 and up to 50 years for those who reach a rate of 500 CD4.
Simply speaking, it means that for someone who is diagnosed positive at 25 years of age, "as long as they remain under control, they will be able to live without problems up to 75 years of age," explained the scientist interviewed.
In order to put this progress in context, it is important to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years on average.
While mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died as a result of AIDS has increased from 6.678 cases in 2007 to 4.862 in 2011 (according to the annual report of UNAIDS), it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60% of patients registered on the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 died until May of this year; however, we have been assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
Then why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the past 12 years at least, we've never missed drugs, the problem is that patients are at very advanced stages because they don't know they're infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
It gives us an indisputable fact "nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what it takes to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to carry out earlier diagnoses and, for that, we must propose massive screening tests, to all those who ask for it".
The experts and members of the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as well as the patients themselves, like Fabrizio, who had to do his test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done so and, despite his young age, he was already carrying AIDS and suffering from Kaposi sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, it's better for me to have fun three times a week," they say, "I don't.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medication.
To date, his parents only know that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALICO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the march of World AIDS Day.
If they do the test, if they take risks, the sooner they know if they are HIV positive and the better, and if they already have the diagnosis, they need to know that we can live like everyone else, by being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara, who embraced the cause of HIV.
And the biggest thing is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to this, "we actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packages of one hundred, it is very good, but the result, that still today, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", asked with sarcasm and value judgments by social workers, guidance counsellors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers do not want to hear, says the journalist.
He proposed reorienting this ineffective distribution; that condoms not only be sold at the counters, but that they be found in the public toilet dispensers and in the places that young people frequent.
This is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it a question of paying them the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González had said when asked if there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
"It's not how sexuality works, it's best to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active," he said.
The figures in Jalisco
There are 13.435 cumulative cases (12.158 AIDS and 1.317 HIV).
The State is the 4th state of the country in number of new cases and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th for the number of HIV patients.
92% of the infections occur by sex, 6% by blood and 2% by perinatal route.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for each case recorded, there are 4 or 5 people who ignore it.
A judgment ratified on appeal by a US court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group's debt through commercial bankruptcy in Mexico. The scenario causes a bad precedent for all domestic companies with ramifications in the neighbouring country and solvency problems.
It therefore seems that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with the starry banner, on the other side of international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the judgment handed down on 15 June by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves defenceless Mexican companies facing the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico's main glass manufacturer to bring the case before the US Supreme Court on the basis of three inconsistencies.
First, while the judge pointed out that creditors had to register under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Appeal Court, sitting in New Orleans, stated that the main proceeding was formal commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
Indeed, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law was created for this purpose by taking the American Law Institute as an arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment establishes that without the inter-company vote, recognised in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, Vitro's subsidiaries' debts to the parent company, the majority required for approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, Vitro's case is not the first to use this plan.
Here there are half a dozen examples, among which Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose debts had been guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcy.
Moreover, what is certain is that, since the votes of the subsidiaries remained, in any way the creditors of Vitro who fought against this in the courts of the United States, i.e. the "vautour" funds like Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained the majority.
The vote would have been 45 votes to 37.
A data omitted by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro was blamed for the difficult situation he had been facing since 2008 without stopping at the serious economic crisis facing the United States, affecting the country's costs.
For the moment, the Gonzalez Sada family society will appeal to the same court of appeal for the vote to take place in its entirety, i.e. with the five magistrates, since only three had voted.
The insurance claim will claim non-prosperity and require a review of the trial by a higher court, in this case the Supreme Court of Justice of the United States.
The most serious thing is that the court ignored a document sent by the Government of Mexico on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the court") in which the procedure followed by Vitro under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act was detailed, noting that this would release it from the agreements signed by both countries to bring it to the same level as paragraph 15 of the US Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, he pointed out that the country had followed the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules for cross-border insolvency, which ensured fairness for debtors and creditors.
Two-part carbbling: they run astray Vitro and they run astray the country.
