Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Battleball is my whole life"
The globe-trottor of basketball "Hetin" Reyes spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, travelled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as great as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a brain hemorrhage condemned him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, player of the national basketball team, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I have worn several hats in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," recalls Reyes during a visit of Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he resides with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
Basketball is my whole life.
Reyes doesn't exaggerate when he makes this statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that recall his extraordinary itinerary, bear witness to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he loves most are those who remind him of his time as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid 1950s until 1982, after having spent 15 years as co-manager or manager of the team.
"It was my best years, the ones I took the most advantage of because I had the chance to compete in eight Vaqueros championships from 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
That's a lot of years of satisfaction, including the five championships from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired from the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead of the team," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been a leader here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), telling me: "I have a big player for you, he's two meters tall.
Do you want to?"
That's how to start Mincy, one of Puerto Rico's best players.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and who was one of the best shooters.
I remember he said that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win one championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He was delighted with the Vaqueros championship with Gaussus, but only remotely since in 1988 he was already the great manito of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of his loads and Mincy's on the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we came fourth and we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge hadn't made us play the last game again," Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Team the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, just like the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite was the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won the gold and we beat the US team, which was quite similar to the bronze team that won the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world of 90 because of a knee problem.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy at the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourrutiner replacing the players suspended by the imbroglio of the Pan Am Games of Mar del Plata, we have won gold against all prognosis.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, this is Piculín Ortiz.
His statistics on international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level as has Piculín.
And that doesn't take into account his trajectory in the different leagues he played for.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very difficult to say.
We had a good team composed of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I like the work Leo Arill does.
For you, what is your greatest success in the federation?
Having been part of the most glorious period of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s the BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What's left for you to do?
There are things I would have liked to put in place, such as the regionalization of minor categories.
For example, Ponce's boys play only in their area and only face teams from other parts of the island during national playoffs.
Today, young people travel and play too much when this is not necessarily necessary.
At least I saw the advantage of mandatory certifications and courses for leaders, field staff and referees.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, watch clips of my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and, from time to time, attend basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth (Texas), made himself known worldwide by John Ross Ewing's leading role, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he embodied an unscrupulous, fearsome and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of avarice in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night of the complications of a cancer, according to a statement from the family sent to The Associated Press for the Warner Bros., production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, again playing the ironic role he loved most," the family said.
Larry's family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who was interpreting his wife's role in the original series and in the sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a hospital in Dallas, said her press officer, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I'm going to miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Doctors had diagnosed Larry Hagman with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and had acknowledged that he had been drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995, he was detected with a malignant tumour in the liver and was transplanted.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made himself known on television as an ordinary type in the series "Jinny of My Dreams" broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In her, he interpreted the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered an attractive genius, interpreted by Barbara Eden, and took her home.
He also played in two comedies that remained on the air for a short time, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his roles in the cinema are roles well received by the critic in "The band", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the deliciously detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman enjoyed his greatest success.
The CBS drama series on the Ewing clan and their loved ones was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who killed J.R.?", invented to maintain suspense around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, generated speculation around the world and millions of dollars played in bets.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in an episode of November 1980, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screen and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had made her pregnant and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reasons to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable but charismaticly smiling man: a dishonest entrepreneur and unfaithful husband who was trying to get his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) interned.
"I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R," Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "Ci-gît l'honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, coprotagonist of the original series, remembered this Friday of Hagman as a man " immense, both on the small screen and in life".
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the heart of each of us, who have had the chance to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the channel TNT.
The recording of five episodes is already over for the second season and a sixth is under way, the channel informed.
For the time being, neither Warner nor TNT have reported on how Hagman's death will be integrated into the series.
