A course on the "End of the World" has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religious teacher Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hook there: the end of the "big count" of the Mayan calendar on December 21, to which many people refer as proof of the imminent end of the world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what was waiting for him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax abyss that some have nicknamed "the Armageddon of debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where the Christian theorists of late times thought the apocalypse would trigger.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," Professor Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey) this week.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, it was a very good time.
And you have to remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in apocalypse.
And he's not the only teacher to give classes on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
In Temple, assistant professor Barry Vacker delivers the course "Media, culture and the end of the world".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides a certain human conduct.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real life examples.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible," said Vacker.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply entitled "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world does not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the imminent "desaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, which does not leave students of any choice but to work "until the very night of the end of the supposed world," said Restall.
The courses were quite popular.
"It was completed in two hours," said Restall about his 35-student course for high-level students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves," says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of Revelation, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in Psychology and Nursing, claims to have viewed all the apocalyptic films.
"I had never heard of a course teaching this subject," he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone a teacher, told us that we believe in the end date of the world on December 21.
"Our first project dealt with Mayan prophecy, and in a way we discredited it," says Julie Zegle, a senior student at Temple, 21 years old and from West Chester.
The Maya have never predicted the end of the world, it is only a key date on the calendar, said Restall.
But I concede that there is an anxiety related to apocalypse in Western culture, dating back centuries, which makes people react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has led to an increase in these speculations.
"In other parts of the world, people don't think about that," he says.
This is mostly the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is teaching in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew that we were teaching here on "the end of the world".
"The Philippines does not participate at the end of the world," he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall points out that over the years, we have talked about the many supposed dates of the last judgment, and he says that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will begin immediately to think about the next date" or to philosopherize the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a 7-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Many told us that they were thinking of going to "end-of-the-world" parties.
"Sometimes I call friends and we laugh at them together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
